<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<subsection xml:id="aa-section-turntable-subsection-j" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Expanding the total derivative of <m>\hat{j}</m></title>

  <p>
    We can use the chain rule to expand <m>\dfrac{D \hat{j}}{Dt}</m>:
  </p>

  <p>
    <md xml:id="eqn-total-derivative-j-full" number="yes"> 
        \frac{D \hat{j}}{Dt}
        =
        \frac{\partial \hat{j}}{\partial \lambda}
        \frac{D \lambda}{Dt}
        +
        \frac{\partial \hat{j}}{\partial R}
        \frac{DR}{Dt}
        +
        \frac{\partial \hat{j}}{\partial z}
        \frac{Dz}{Dt}
    </md>
  </p>

  <p>
    The second term on the right-hand side of <xref ref="eqn-total-derivative-j-full" text="type-global" />
    is <m>\vec{0}</m> since <m>\hat{j}</m> does not change orientation if placed at a different radius
    while holding <m>\lambda</m> and <m>z</m> constant,
    and therefore <m>\dfrac{\partial \hat{j}}{\partial R} = \vec{0}</m>.
    Furthermore, as noted in <xref ref="aa-section-turntable-subsection-i" text="type-global" />,
    the point does not move from the edge of the turntable,
    and so <m>\dfrac{DR}{Dt} = 0</m>.
    Likewise, the third term on the right-hand size of <xref ref="eqn-total-derivative-j-full" text="type-global" />
    is <m>\vec{0}</m> since <m>\hat{j}</m> does not change orientation if placed at a different height above or below the turntable
    while holding <m>\lambda</m> and <m>R</m> constant,
    and therefore <m>\dfrac{\partial \hat{j}}{\partial z} = \vec{0}</m>.
    Furthermore, as noted in <xref ref="aa-section-turntable-subsection-i" text="type-global" />,
    the point does not move above or below the edge of the turntable,
    and so <m>\dfrac{Dz}{Dt} = 0</m>.
    Therefore, <xref ref="eqn-total-derivative-j-full" text="type-global" /> reduces to
  </p>

  <p>
    <md xml:id="eqn-total-derivative-j-reduced" number="yes"> 
        \frac{D \hat{j}}{Dt}
        =
        \frac{\partial \hat{j}}{\partial \lambda}
        \frac{D \lambda}{Dt}
    </md>
  </p>

  <p>
    To evaluate <m>\dfrac{\partial \hat{j}}{\partial \lambda}</m>,
    we consider the change in <m>\hat{j}</m>'s orientation
    when its anchoring point is fixed to the edge of the turntable
    and sweeps through angular displacement <m>\delta \lambda</m> over time <m>\delta t</m>,
    as shown in <xref ref="aa-turntable-j-start" text="type-global" /> below.
    <m>\hat{j}_1</m> is the initial position of <m>\hat{j}</m>,
    and <m>\hat{j}_2</m> is the final position of <m>\hat{j}</m> after time <m>\delta t</m> has passed
    and it has swept through angular displacement <m>\delta \lambda</m>.
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="aa-turntable-j-start">
    <caption>
      Unit direction vectors <m>\hat{j}_1</m> and <m>\hat{j}_2</m> at two nearby points at radius <m>R</m> to the turntable of
      <xref ref="aa-turntable-setup" text="type-global" />
      and separated by angular displacement <m>\delta \lambda</m>.
    </caption>
    <image source="images/aa-turntable-j-start.png" width="60%">
      <shortdescription>
        Two unit direction vectors at two nearby points
        on the edge of a circular disk rotating counter-clockwise about its center viewed from above.
        The vectors point inward toward the center of the disk.
      </shortdescription>
    </image>
  </figure>

  <p>
    Fixing the tails of <m>\hat{j}_1</m> and <m>\hat{j}_2</m> together in
    <xref ref="aa-turntable-j-zoom" text="type-global" /> below
    reveals that <m>\delta \lambda</m> is the angle swept out between them
    and <m>\vec{\delta j}</m> is the vector difference between them.
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="aa-turntable-j-zoom">
    <caption>
      Reproduction of <m>\hat{j}_1</m> and <m>\hat{j}_2</m> from <xref ref="aa-turntable-j-start" text="type-global" />.
      When the tails of the vectors are fixed together,
      they are separated by angle <m>\delta \lambda</m> and their vector difference is <m>\vec{\delta j}</m>.
    </caption>
    <image source="images/aa-turntable-j-zoom.png" width="30%">
      <shortdescription>
        Two unit direction vectors with their tails fixed together
        and the angle swept out between them and their vector difference annotated.
      </shortdescription>
    </image>
  </figure>

  <p>
    Reproducing <xref ref="aa-turntable-j-start" text="type-global" />
    with the tail of <m>\hat{j}_1</m> moved to the tail of <m>\hat{j}_2</m> and <m>\vec{\delta j}</m> additionally included
    in <xref ref="aa-turntable-j-end" text="type-global" /> below makes these relationships even clearer.
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="aa-turntable-j-end">
    <caption>
      Reproduction of <xref ref="aa-turntable-j-start" text="type-global" />
      with the tail of <m>\hat{j}_1</m> fixed to the tail of <m>\hat{j}_2</m>.
      As shown in <xref ref="aa-turntable-j-zoom" text="type-global" />,
      <m>\hat{j}_1</m> and <m>\hat{j}_2</m> are separated by angle <m>\delta \lambda</m>
      and their vector difference is <m>\vec{\delta j}</m>.
    </caption>
    <image source="images/aa-turntable-j-end.png" width="60%">
      <shortdescription>
        Two unit direction vectors with their tails fixed together
        on the edge of a circular disk rotating counter-clockwise about its center viewed from above.
      </shortdescription>
    </image>
  </figure>

  <p>
    Again, we can use the arc length formula to approximate <m>|\vec{\delta j}|</m>,
    and we can take advantage of the fact that,
    since <m>\hat{j}</m> is a unit direction vector,
    <m>|\hat{j}| = 1</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    <md number="yes">
        |\vec{\delta j}|
        = |\hat{j_1}| \, \delta \lambda
        = |\hat{j_2}| \, \delta \lambda
        = |\hat{j}| \, \delta \lambda
        = \delta \lambda
    </md>
  </p>

  <p>
    Therefore,
  </p>

  <p>
    <md number="yes">
        \frac{|\vec{\delta j}|}{\delta t}
        =
        \frac{|\vec{\delta j}|}{\delta \lambda}
        \frac{\delta \lambda}{\delta t}
        =
        \frac{\delta \lambda}{\delta \lambda}
        \frac{\delta \lambda}{\delta t}
        =
        \frac{\delta \lambda}{\delta t}
    </md>
  </p>

  <p>
    From <xref ref="aa-turntable-j-end" text="type-global" />,
    we can see that as <m>\delta t \to 0</m>,
    <m>\delta \lambda \to 0</m> and <m>\vec{\delta j}</m> points to the local left,
    which coincides with the <m>-\hat{i}</m> direction.
    So
  </p>

  <p>
    <md xml:id="eqn-total-derivative-j-final" number="yes"> 
        \lim_{\delta t \to 0}
        \frac{\vec{\delta j}}{\delta t}
        =
        \frac{D \hat{j}}{D t}
        =
        \lim_{\delta t \to 0}
        \frac{\delta \lambda}{\delta t} (-\hat{i})
        =
        -\frac{D\lambda}{Dt} \, \hat{i}
        =
        -\Omega \, \hat{i}
    </md>
  </p>

</subsection>